t";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2297:"<p>Today we’re happy to launch <a href="http://themeforest.net/item/concept-living-layers-woocommerce-theme/5388303?ref=obox&amp;utm_source=blog.layers&amp;utm_medium=link&amp;utm_campaign=Blog%3A%20Concept%20Living%20Launch%20Post">Concept Living</a>, a WordPress furniture theme for furniture retailers. Originally called Store and built on Obox Themes technology, we decided that Layers offered a perfect opportunity to modernize it.</p>\n<p>During Obox Themes’ 7 year existence we have created well over 100 themes, some for WordPress, some for Tumblr, some for Posterous… but mostly WordPress.</p>\n<p>Of those themes there have been some stand out performers, including <a href="http://themeforest.net/item/gigawatt-wordpress-video-theme/492944?ref=obox">Gigawatt</a>, <a href="http://themeforest.net/item/retail-therapy-multipurpose-ecommerce-theme/5636873?ref=obox">Retail Therapy</a>, <a href="http://themeforest.net/item/the-writer-premium-wordpress-blogging-theme/5908925?ref=obox">The Writer</a> etc. So when we sat down to decide what our next Layers theme was going to be we realized that the answer may be staring us in the face &#8211; why not take our best Obox Themes and give them a fresh coat of paint and a brand new foundation?</p>\n<p>New features include a mobile first design, multiple header layouts, StoreKit integration, Layers page building functionality and much more.</p>\n<p>Check out the <a href="http://themeforest.net/item/concept-living-layers-woocommerce-theme/full_screen_preview/5388303?ref=obox&amp;utm_source=blog.layers&amp;utm_medium=link&amp;utm_campaign=Blog%3A%20Concept%20Living%20Launch%20Post">demo</a> or find out more by visiting <a href="http://themeforest.net/item/concept-living-layers-woocommerce-theme/5388303?ref=obox&amp;utm_source=blog.layers&amp;utm_medium=link&amp;utm_campaign=Blog%3A%20Concept%20Living%20Launch%20Post">Concept Living</a> on Themeforest.</p>\n<p>We look forward to bringing you much more of our finest work in the near future.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/announcing-concept-living-a-wordpress-furniture-theme/">Refreshing a best seller with Concept Living, a WordPress Furniture Theme</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com">Layers</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:91:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/announcing-concept-living-a-wordpress-furniture-theme/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:48:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"Introducing Layers Pro, the best extension we’ve ever made";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:85:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/introducing-layers-pro-best-extension-weve-ever-made/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:94:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/introducing-layers-pro-best-extension-weve-ever-made/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 18 Nov 2015 08:45:45 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Layers";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"layers updates";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://www.layerswp.com/?p=2001";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:380:"<p>Unlock customizability in the Layers framework with extended control over design and layout settings.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/introducing-layers-pro-best-extension-weve-ever-made/">Introducing Layers Pro, the best extension we’ve ever made</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com">Layers</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Marc Perel";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4851:"<p>The number one request we get from Layers users is the ability to do more. More customizability, more colors, more control.</p>\n<p>When we set about building Layers we wanted to focus on the most important needs of a website and then work our way up from there. Our number one focus was to avoid throwing the kitchen sink at you.</p>\n<p>The strategy has worked well, with tons of great sites being built, but as people have conquered the logic of page building so they have reached a point where more control is needed.</p>\n<p><a href="http://www.layerswp.com/layers-pro/">Layers Pro</a> bridges the gap between a solid site and being really creative.</p>\n<h3><b>What does Layers Pro give me?</b></h3>\n<p>There are a number of features that Layers Pro enables when you install the extension on your site:</p>\n<h4><b>Header Styling</b></h4>\n<p>Finally you can “make the logo bigger” with flexible logo size options, and if our small, medium, large and massive  presets aren’t perfect for you then we’ve included ‘custom’ resizing too.</p>\n<p>Height adjustment and menu spacing has been included for that pixel perfect header layout.</p>\n<p>Another big request was the ability to customize your site menus, which is now possible with colors, spacing, shadows and text-transforming.</p>\n<h4><b>Blog Controls</b></h4>\n<p>From day one you can determine exactly which elements you’d like to display on your list and post pages:</p>\n<p><strong>These include the toggling of:</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Featured Images</li>\n<li>Post Dates</li>\n<li>Post Categories</li>\n<li>Post Tags</li>\n<li>Post Author</li>\n<li>Post Excerpt lengths and the “Read More” button text can be changed too.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4><b>More Color Options</b></h4>\n<p>You requested deeper color customization, so we went to town…</p>\n<p>Color options are now split into contextual areas which cuts out the need to click in and out of accordions to get to the place you want. It’s a massive UX improvement that’s performed well in testing.</p>\n<p>Button customization is also vastly improved with the addition of border color, thickness and radius. You can determine button styling on both light and dark backgrounds.</p>\n<p>Menu coloring, blog post coloring, widgets and more have been included in <a href="http://www.layerswp.com/layers-pro/">Layers Pro</a>.</p>\n<p>We will constantly be adding new color customization parameters to Layers Pro so that you have even more control over your site without requiring knowledge of code.</p>\n<h4><b>Tweak the Footer</b></h4>\n<p>New footer options have been added with the inclusion of a new height setting and color customization.</p>\n<h4><b>4 New Widgets and a great update to the Content Widget</b></h4>\n<p>A major part of <a href="http://www.layerswp.com/layers-pro/">Layers Pro</a> is the inclusion of new widgets which allow for different ways to display content:</p>\n<p>The <strong>Tab</strong> and <strong>Accordion</strong> widgets enable you to present multiple pages or paragraphs of content in one place. Use it for sequential information such as steps or product tours, or group information that relates to each other.</p>\n<p>We’ve included a new <strong>Post Carousel</strong> widget which outputs your latest blog posts and can slide via controls or automatically with a timer of your choice.</p>\n<p>A much needed <strong>Call to Action</strong> widget is also available from today which you can use to direct user to your products, important blog posts or contact page with multiple buttons under a big header, you no longer have to use the Slider Widget. With the ability to include multiple buttons you can invite them to try your product or read more about it. The choice is yours.</p>\n<p>The most powerful widget, the Content Widget, has also received a subtle but important update which now allows you to add custom class name to individual columns. This will give CSS developers much more flexibility when customizing client or personal websites.</p>\n<h4><b>This is just the start</b></h4>\n<p>We want to ensure that Layers Pro takes the free version of Layers and turns it up to 11. The features we’ve announced today are just the first step in what we hope will be a long update cycle with more features added every month. So if you have any special requests let us know!</p>\n<p><a href="http://www.layerswp.com/layers-pro/">Find out more about Layers Pro</a> or go to directly to CodeCanyon and <a href="http://codecanyon.net/item/layers-pro-extended-customization-for-layers/11225042?ref=obox">purchase it</a> right away.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/introducing-layers-pro-best-extension-weve-ever-made/">Introducing Layers Pro, the best extension we’ve ever made</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com">Layers</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:90:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/introducing-layers-pro-best-extension-weve-ever-made/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"12";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:48:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:38:"How to Speed Up Your WordPress Website";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/how-to-speed-up-your-website/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/how-to-speed-up-your-website/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sat, 07 Nov 2015 13:45:06 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"Tips";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"development";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"wordpress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://www.layerswp.com/?p=1794";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:402:"<p>One of the most critical ingredients in your website''s success recipe is its performance, in this post we give you some tips on how to improve your WordPress site speed.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/how-to-speed-up-your-website/">How to Speed Up Your WordPress Website</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com">Layers</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Vail Joy";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15403:"<p>Performance is based on several factors such as interface usability, load times and mobile compatibility, but the load time is where things usually go quickly downhill.</p>\n<p><a href="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/every-second-counts.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1989 size-full" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/every-second-counts.png" alt="" width="990" height="914" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/every-second-counts-300x277.png 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/every-second-counts.png 990w" sizes="(max-width: 990px) 100vw, 990px" /></a></p>\n<p>It is surprisingly easy to end up with a sluggish WordPress website, no matter how minimal you may have set out to make it. Little things from your web host choice all the way to your WordPress configuration can lead to slow loading times for visitors, and according to Kissmetrics, nearly 40% of people will surf somewhere else if the page takes more than a few seconds to display anything.</p>\n<p>Slow performance is especially problematic for online stores, where you may have several visitors performing complex actions on your site at a single time.  A majority of shoppers were found in this study to be less likely to buy from a site that is slow or displaying other problems that keep them from having a smooth experience.</p>\n<p><a href="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/every-second-counts-02.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1990 size-full" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/every-second-counts-02.png" alt="" width="990" height="1229" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/every-second-counts-02-242x300.png 242w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/every-second-counts-02-825x1024.png 825w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/every-second-counts-02.png 990w" sizes="(max-width: 990px) 100vw, 990px" /></a></p>\n<p>While 30% are pretty patient, willing to wait 6-10 seconds for a page load, you want to aim for less than that. Most sites running WordPress can load between 1-3 seconds.</p>\n<p>Here are a few effective tips for troubleshooting slow performance in the front-end of your site, and getting it running quickly and efficiently.</p>\n<h3>Why Your Site is Slow</h3>\n<p>The first step to troubleshooting a slow site or preparing a new one for snappy performance is understanding where slow-downs originate. The most common cause of slow page loads is slow internet speed, which is nothing you can control, but there are a number of things to check in your WordPress setup.</p>\n<p>Things that can aggravate site load times in a site using Layers are:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Cheap (slow) web hosting</li>\n<li>Low database memory allocation on your server</li>\n<li>Too many plugins activated</li>\n<li>Large file size of content such as HD images</li>\n<li>Script conflicts between plugins or large numbers of errors being generated</li>\n<li>3rd Party content including videos, hosted files or banner ads that take too long to connect to the host</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Your theme choice can be a factor in load speed as well. Some themes package a colossal amount of scripting, animations and other libraries that load on ever page.</p>\n<p>Layers is specifically designed to avoid this kind of &#8220;bloat factor&#8221; by building out functionality already present in the WordPress core, the aim of which is a minimal load.</p>\n<p>We also <a href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/07/how-to-speed-up-the-wordpress-customizer/" target="_blank">do regular speed optimizations inside and out</a> to stay on top of performance considerations within the limitations of what we can do from a theme development standpoint.</p>\n<h3>What You Can Do</h3>\n<p>When testing your site, use a demo URL like <a href="http://tools.pingdom.com/fpt/#!/eAiQ2E/http://vailjoy.com/layers/" target="_blank">this one</a> as a benchmark. This demo is installed on WordPress Hosting at BlueHost does not have any caching enabled, and receives only medium traffic.</p>\n<p>By comparison, <a href="http://tools.pingdom.com/fpt/#!/ehYIpw/http://layerswp.com" target="_blank">this site</a>, also running Layers, has a <a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/reference/child-theme/" target="_blank">child theme</a> and several plugins, runs on a WordPress multi-site on a different host, and receives high traffic. Both load in under 2 seconds.</p>\n<p>While the theme files themselves won&#8217;t cause slowdowns, certain <em>functionality</em> in your theme may support <strong>content</strong> that causes slowdowns. The fix typically depends on your setup. Here are some things you can do to troubleshoot:</p>\n<h4>Evaluate Internet Speed</h4>\n<p>Sometimes slow loading is just your connection being slow, or your host being slow. The best test is to ask someone in a different location to try visiting your URL and see how their experience compares.</p>\n<p>Your host can also test the load and explain any limitations of your hosting. If you have a large photography website, or an eCommerce site with a lot of traffic for example, you may need to upgrade to a VPS or WordPress hosting tier to avoid your traffic being throttled.</p>\n<h4>Run an Initial Speed Test</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://tools.pingdom.com/fpt/">Pingdom</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://developers.google.com/speed/pagespeed/">Google Pagespeed</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Both of these resources will scan your site for specific load inhibitors and produce a report. Keep in mind that it is going to advise you about all inhibitors, whether they are a real problem or not.</p>\n<p>On Pingdom, all resources in your homepage will be listed. Typically the theme sylesheets load first, followed by plugins and scripting, and finally, the assets on the page, such as images, will load last and typically take the longest.</p>\n<p>Pay special attention to the very first ping, which is how long it takes the browser to communicate with the server and receive a response from your domain. Long load times here indicate a DNS or server issue, so it may be worth running a “DNS Health” test on your main website URL.</p>\n<p>For Google Pagespeed, ensure you are looking at the <strong>Desktop</strong> diagnostics tab. Items in the Red section of Pagespeed are the things to watch out for.  If you are not familiar with the terminology used, below is a brief outline of what some of the results mean and what you should do about them or not:</p>\n<h4>Optimize Images</h4>\n<p>If you have a significant amount of graphics or images on your site, they can cause a lot of load time if they are not as small in file size as possible. In many cases, the savings are marginal and not necessary, but if you see the size reduction is more than a few hundred kb, you probably need to re-process and re-upload your images (details in the next section)</p>\n<h4>Reduce Server Response Time</h4>\n<p>Cheap hosting often means slow speeds, and can be made worse by other sites on the same host taking up too much bandwidth or database memory. Contact your host if this is brought up as an issue.</p>\n<h4>Reduce Content Loading Before the Fold (aka render-blocking content)</h4>\n<p>This is a pretty idealistic option and one you can’t do much to directly influence, as WordPress sites need to load a measure of data, scripting or stylesheets at the beginning of the page.</p>\n<p>Layers is specifically optimized for load, and will not load anything at the beginning that is not explicitly required to load that way.</p>\n<p>Your plugins and <a href="http://kb.oboxthemes.com/glossary/page-template/">page templates</a> will also dynamically load in scripts or styles being used on that page, and it all happens in the header. In most cases, this is not the cause of your site being slow, but can be if the page is looking for offsite content.</p>\n<h4>Reduce Offsite Content</h4>\n<p>This refers to functionality or content in your site that comes from somewhere else, including Google Fonts, Twitter or Facebook widgets, sharing buttons, or hosted scripts like Google Analytics, Vimeo videos, hotlinked images and so on.</p>\n<p>If these sites are experiencing downtime or slowdowns, your site will be forced to wait until a timeout limit is exceeded and an error is produced or the page skips the element and keeps loading. This should not deter you from using these services, but is important to be aware of the potential impacts.</p>\n<h4>Check Your Content</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>If you have a theme with a lot of <strong>video content </strong>that uses the Layers video embed url field in posts, ensure the <a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/reference/oembed/">oEmbed</a> url starts with //: or http:// and not https://</li>\n<li>For sites with a lot of <strong>images</strong>, ensure images are optimized for the web by saving them as JPGs, scaling them down to no larger than 2000px wide or less than 2MB in file size.\n<ul>\n<li>See <a href="http://kb.oboxthemes.com/articles/how-to-prepare-photos-for-your-website/">How to Prepare Photos for Your Website</a></li>\n<li>Download and run the <strong>Regenerate Thumbnails</strong> or <strong>WPSmush It</strong> plugin</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Do not hotlink images. In other words, ensure all images on your site are hosted on your site and not from a 3rd party website, flickr, instagram or similar. These options are great for creating galleries using thumbnails and so on, but if these sites timeout on loading large images, your site will be slow.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Verify Plugin Compatibility</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Temporarily deactivate all plugins<strong> </strong>(excluding WooCommerce), then clear your browser cache and test the load again. If it is improved, you will need to reactivate plugins one at a time to figure out if there is a conflict, or reduce the number of plugins you have activated.</li>\n<li>Use as few plugins for front-end stuff as possible. Most hosts only allow between 32 and 64M of database memory for shared hosting, which can be quickly exceeded on sites running a ton of plugins. Evaluate how important a plugin is to your site and decide if it can be removed or consolidate by finding plugins that do more than one thing.</li>\n<li>Always use plugins that are actively developed or supported by their author, are cleared for use on the current WordpPress version, and have a decent rating (make sure 5 star plugins have several hundred votes, not just a handful, which can be very misleading!)</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you are using WordPress SEO by Yoast, go to <strong><span class="admin-menu-item">SEO</span></strong> &gt; <strong><span class="admin-menu-item">TITLES</span> </strong>and uncheck the <em>Force Rewrite Titles</em> option. You can check the <a href="http://wordpress.org/support/plugin/wordpress-seo" target="_blank">plugin’s support forums</a> for examples of others affected by slowdowns and some possible solutions. If you find this helped, see the following for advice on optimizing settings.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>If you are using <strong>WP Super Cache</strong>, clear it, deactivate it, and replace it with a plugin that is known for less problems such as Quick Cache</li>\n<li>If you are using <strong>W3 Total Cache</strong>, go to <span class="admin-menu-item"><strong>PERFORMANCE</strong> </span>&gt; <span class="admin-menu-item">GENERAL SETTINGS</span> and uncheck the <em>Page Cache</em> option, then empty the cache and re-test.</li>\n<li>WooCommerce sites using W3 Total Cache must check this:\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://kb.oboxthemes.com/articles/woocommerce-order-status-not-changing-on-order-complete/">WooCommerce: Order status not changing on order complete</a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Any plugin that imports data from another site will kill performance. This includes plugins that pull in feeds from an RSS source, social network plugins that pull in status updates, Flickr plugins that auto-post photos, and so on.</li>\n<li>WooCommerce sites should have SSL enabled only for the shop pages. Do not force it on the rest of your site as it just increases the amount of checks on the server end, unless you are using Obox Social Commerce or another Facebook app that requires full domain SSL. Contact your host for help with this step if you are eunsure how to target specific parts of your site or don’t know how to wildcard urls.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Install a Caching Plugin</h3>\n<p>I know, I know, we just said you should reduce the number of plugins installed, and have pointed out some issues with some caching plugins, but the bottom line is that when configured correctly, they increase speed for subsequent visits to your site substantially and do not take much memory.</p>\n<p>If you want to forego using a plugin, check with your host on what kind of Server-side caching is available, such as Cloudflare, AWS, or Varnish</p>\n<p><strong>For advanced admins</strong> or sites that need a lot of control on Caching options, we recommend W3 Total Cache <strong>without Page Caching enabled</strong>. Please see the author’s documentation on configuration, and if you use WooCommerce, <a href="http://kb.oboxthemes.com/articles/woocommerce-order-status-not-changing-on-order-complete/" target="_blank">see this article!</a></p>\n<p><strong>For beginners</strong> or basic blog/portfolio sites, Quick Cache is a solid and actively developed plugin.</p>\n<p><strong>For advice and tips</strong> on which plugins are tested on Obox Themes and which our customers have used., or which plugins to watch out for, see</p>\n<p class="post-title"><a title="Plugin Compatibility" href="http://docs.layerswp.com/plugin-compatibility/" target="_blank">What plugins are compatible with Layers?</a></p>\n<h3>Increase Memory</h3>\n<p>See the following for advice from WordPress on how you can attempt to increase the memory allocated to your site. Some hosts do not allow edits to the php.ini, so you may need to contact them for help and troubleshooting on this step.</p>\n<p>WordPress Codex:<a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Editing_wp-config.php#Increasing_memory_allocated_to_PHP" target="_blank"> Increasing Memory Limit</a></p>\n<h3 class="section-title">Verify Server-side configurations</h3>\n<p>Things like extra content in your <strong>wp_config.php</strong> can trigger a ton of errors which you may not be seeing on the front-end, but which will slow the site.</p>\n<p>Server-side security or <strong>.htaccess</strong> problems can also cause slowdowns with WordPress trying to write <a class="glossaryLink" title="Glossary: Permalinks" href="http://kb.oboxthemes.com/glossary/permalinks/">permalinks</a> or execute other functionality. This is typically a step you will need your host to help you troubleshoot if nothing else is helping.</p>\n<p>The following article offers some great advice for optimizing your setup, specifically when working with caching plugins like W3 Total Cache:</p>\n<p><a href="http://blog.newrelic.com/2013/02/07/web-performance-optimization-automation/" target="_blank">Web Performance Optimizations for WordPress</a></p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/how-to-speed-up-your-website/">How to Speed Up Your WordPress Website</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com">Layers</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:66:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/how-to-speed-up-your-website/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:49:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:8:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:66:"The Essential Guide to WordPress Theme Customization for Beginners";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:99:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/the-essential-guide-to-wordpress-theme-customization-for-beginners/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:107:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/the-essential-guide-to-wordpress-theme-customization-for-beginners/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 10 Nov 2015 13:37:15 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"Tips";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"development";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"wordpress theme customization";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://www.layerswp.com/?p=1787";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:623:"<p>Even if you know enough about WordPress theme customization to be dangerous, there are probably things you''re doing the hard way, or the wrong way. Thankfully, there are many simple things you can do to customize the look and feel of your site that don''t require editing any files, or for you to be a professional developer.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/the-essential-guide-to-wordpress-theme-customization-for-beginners/">The Essential Guide to WordPress Theme Customization for Beginners</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com">Layers</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:9:"enclosure";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:68:"http://docs.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/edit-widgets.mp4";s:6:"length";s:6:"981168";s:4:"type";s:9:"video/mp4";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Vail Joy";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16321:"<p>If you’re new to WordPress, you&#8217;ve probably arrived at that confusing question of &#8220;How can I change how my site looks?&#8221; Layers gives you a solid set of beginner tools for customizing layouts, colors and fonts, but what if you want to do something more specific, like add background texture to inside pages, or change the hover color on your nav menu?</p>\n<p>Even if you know enough about WordPress theme customization to be dangerous, there are probably things you&#8217;re doing the hard way, or the wrong way.</p>\n<p>Thankfully, there are many simple things you can do to customize the look and feel of your site that don&#8217;t require editing any files, or for you to be a professional developer.</p>\n<div style="width: 640px; " class="wp-video"><!--[if lt IE 9]><script>document.createElement(''video'');</script><![endif]-->\n<video class="wp-video-shortcode" id="video-1787-1" width="640" height="360" preload="metadata" controls="controls"><source type="video/mp4" src="http://docs.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/edit-widgets.mp4?_=1" /><a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/edit-widgets.mp4">http://docs.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/edit-widgets.mp4</a></video></div>\n<h3>The WordPress Customizer</h3>\n<p>WordPress is quickly moving towards a visual customization experience that is based on intuitive interfaces, direct front-end editing and layout building with widgets. By default, the WordPress Customizer offers you a preview of your website, a custom logo and favicon setting, a background color option, menu customization and a panel for your sidebar and footer widgets.</p>\n<p>With Layers activated, these options are greatly extended to include logo and menu positions, primary site colors, footer column choices, fonts and more.</p>\n<p>Layers Widgets are your building blocks for creating unique page layouts in combination with the Layers page template, or for customizing widget content look and feel in any widget area of a child theme. The Customizer allows you to see your changes on the front-end while you move things around on the back end.</p>\n<p>You can even take advantage of CSS editing directly from the customizer, which we will get to in a moment.</p>\n<p><a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Appearance_Customize_Screen" target="_blank">Learn more about the WordPress Customizer</a></p>\n<p><iframe width="660" height="371" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/tcC7czcawsY?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>\n<h3>Style Kits</h3>\n<p>If you just want to change the look and feel of your Layers site, but don&#8217;t feel up to a crash course in webpage styling (CSS), Style Kits are a quick and inexpensive way to apply pre-made professional styles to your site without requiring another theme. We even use one here on our blog!</p>\n<p>To get an idea how they work, check out our little <a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/how-to-create-a-style-kit/">Style Kit guide</a> and grab the freebie kit.</p>\n<p>You can find free kits specifically made for Layers around the web or from our <a href="http://codecanyon.net/category/skins/layers-wp-style-kits?ref=obox">Marketplace</a>. Compared to what it costs to hire a designer, Style Kits can save you <em>hundreds of dollars.</em></p>\n<p><a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/product/style-kits/" target="_blank">Learn more about Style Kits</a></p>\n<p><a href="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/devkit-state.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1635" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/devkit-state.png" alt="devkit-state" width="576" height="167" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/devkit-state-300x87.png 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/devkit-state.png 576w" sizes="(max-width: 576px) 100vw, 576px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Custom CSS</h3>\n<p>If you know a thing or two about styling or feel up to learning something new, CSS is the definitive method for customizing your site&#8217;s look and feel. You&#8217;ve probably seen this term used a lot in relation to web design and customization.</p>\n<p>With CSS, you can change colors, fonts, heights, padding, margins and  just about anything that does not compromise the overall structure.</p>\n<p>CSS has three main parts, the <span style="color: #339966;"><strong>selector</strong></span>, the <span style="color: #ff6600;"><strong>property</strong></span> and the <span style="color: #33cccc;"><strong>value.</strong></span> Selectors are determined by the programmer when building the framework for your site. They can be the HTML tags composing the structure of the page, or a <strong>class</strong> name added to the HTML tag.</p>\n<p>For example, the menu links in Layers are <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">a</pre>  HTML elements inside an unordered list <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">ul</pre>  with the class <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">nav-horizontal</pre> . When put together, it would look something like this if we want to change the <span style="color: #ff6600;">color</span> <strong>property</strong> to a <strong>value</strong> of <span style="color: #33cccc;">blue</span>.</p><pre class="crayon-plain-tag">.nav-horizontal li a{color: blue;}</pre><p>At first it may seem complicated, but CSS is the easiest web programming language to begin learning thanks to its semantic quality. Understanding the basics of CSS is an essential skill if you manage websites for yourself or others. It helps you use the huge library of customization tutorials on the internet and our very own Docs site to tweak the look of your site and save money on hiring a designer.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re wondering how you can determine what selectors to use to even begin custom styling, webkit browsers such as Chrome, Firefox and Safari  come with a wonderful inspector tool for viewing the HTML and associated CSS of anything you right-click on.</p>\n<p>Learn more about using this feature in our <a class="question-title" href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/how-to-customize-your-site-with-css/" rel="bookmark">How to Customize Your Site With CSS</a> tutorial.</p>\n<p>We recommend checking out the <a href="https://www.codecademy.com/courses/web-beginner-en-TlhFi/0/1?curriculum_id=50579fb998b470000202dc8b" target="_blank">free CodeAcademy CSS course</a> to get a quick grip on CSS. CodeAcademy uses beginner language and an interactive format for helping you master web languages quickly.</p>\n<p><a href="http://codecanyon.net/user/obox/portfolio?utf8=%E2%9C%93&amp;term=layers&amp;ref=obox&amp;utm_source=blog.layers&amp;utm_medium=link&amp;utm_campaign=Layers%20Blog%3A%20Extensions" target="_blank"><img class="alignnone wp-image-303" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/envato-announcement.jpg" alt="envato-announcement" width="713" height="428" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/envato-announcement-300x180.jpg 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/envato-announcement.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 713px) 100vw, 713px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Plugins &amp; Extensions</h3>\n<p>Just about anything you can think of needing for your website can be done with a plugin or extension, which are how WordPress adds specific functionality to your site.</p>\n<p>Plugins and extensions offer a major benefit in allowing you to pick and choose how to build your site, versus using a theme package with a ton of options and features you may not need which are overwhelming to learn how to configure.</p>\n<p>For example, if you plan to build an online store and know you want to be able to customize the shop a little, add a product tab for Wash &amp; Care instructions, and allow your users to &#8220;Quick View&#8221;the products, you can use Layers with <a href="http://codecanyon.net/item/storekit-woocommerce-for-layers/11223808?ref=obox" target="_blank">StoreKit</a>, <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/woocommerce-poor-guys-swiss-knife/" target="_blank">Poor Guys Swiss Knife</a> and <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/yith-woocommerce-tab-manager/" target="_blank">YITH WooCommerce Tabs</a> for a grand total of $21. That is less than any premium theme and still gets you the support you need where it matters most.</p>\n<h4>What&#8217;s the Difference?</h4>\n<p>An extension differs from a plugin in that it is built for use with a specific framework like Layers or WooCommerce, whereas plugins are not dependent on what else you have installed.</p>\n<p><a href="http://www.layerswp.com/storekit/">StoreKit</a> is an extension for Layers that adds WooCommerce customization and some product widgets you can add to your pages that come with all the cool Layers widget customizability.</p>\n<p>YITH WooCommerce Tabs is an extension for WooCommerce that obviously doesn&#8217;t provide much function if WooCommerce is not installed. Image Widget, or Yoast SEO are both essential plugins for WordPress that work with any theme and do not require other plugins to be installed.</p>\n<p>To find Layers Extensions, visit the <strong>Marketplace</strong> link in your WordPress admin panel. To find WooCommerce extensions, visit the WooCommerce website, or go to <strong>Plugins</strong> &#8211;  <strong>Add New</strong> and search for WooCommerce. This free plugin repository has a near-endless number of excellent plugins you can choose from.</p>\n<h4>How to Choose</h4>\n<p>When choosing free plugins, it is important to check out the <em>Details</em> to ensure the plugin does what you want, is user-friendly, and produces good-looking results. Each plugin has a rating, along with how many installs, and a date it was last updated. Always choose highly-rated plugins that have been updated recently or are verified compatible with your version of WordPress.</p>\n<p>With premium extensions, check what the framework author has to offer before going to independently authored extensions, to ensure the best integration and support options.</p>\n<p>A word of caution &#8211; don&#8217;t go too crazy with the free plugin installs. Not all plugins are created equal, and because they are designed by a huge variety of developers for no cost, they simply can&#8217;t guarantee cross-compatibility with your unique setup.</p>\n<p>In most cases, an actively-developed plugin with a good rating will have very few compatibility issues, but it is always a good idea to check the Support tab of the plugin&#8217;s Details page to see what kind of issues, if any, folks are reporting. <a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/plugin-compatibility/" target="_blank">Learn more about Layers plugin compatibility</a> over on the Layers Docs website.</p>\n<p><a href="http://themeforest.net/user/obox/portfolio?utf8=%E2%9C%93&amp;term=layers?ref=obox"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-85" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/coffee.jpg" alt="coffee" width="660" height="745" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/coffee-266x300.jpg 266w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/coffee.jpg 660w" sizes="(max-width: 660px) 100vw, 660px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Child Themes</h3>\n<p>The final and most thorough way to customize your WordPress site using Layers or any other theme, is through a child theme. A child theme is jut like any other theme except it is able to inherit all of the functionality and front-end structure from Layers (the “parent”)  while including its own special styles and functions.</p>\n<p>You can purchase professionally designed <a href="http://themeforest.net/attributes/framework/layers wp?ref=obox&amp;utm_source=layerswp&amp;utm_medium=cta&amp;utm_content=AllAuthors&amp;utm_campaign=Layers+Blog&amp;clickthrough_id&amp;redirect_back=true">Child Themes</a> for Layers from the Marketplace page in your WordPress admin, or you can make your own.</p>\n<h4 class="section-title">When to Use a Child Theme</h4>\n<p>The division between themes and plugins in WordPress has been a bit blurry for a long time, as both can introduce new functionality to a WordPress install, so you always want to see what can be done with all your other options first.</p>\n<p>You need a Child Theme when:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>You want to re-style a theme without or beyond what the WordPress customizer controls or other plugins allow you to do,</li>\n<li>You want to add a bit of code to a specific place (such as a search field in the header) or</li>\n<li>You want to add custom page templates</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When you need to find a plugin or build an Extension:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>You want to add Custom Post Types</li>\n<li>You want to add Layers Builder Widgets</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Child themes are for presentation, whereas extensions are for extending functionality.</p>\n<h3>Child Themes vs Style Kits</h3>\n<p>As you can see, there are a ton of options for customizing your site with a range of functionality requiring little skill, but two of these may sound a little similar. Both child themes and style kits involve<strong> custom css</strong> to a degree but are not the same.</p>\n<h4><strong>Style Kit</strong></h4>\n<p>Collection of presets generated from the Layers Customizer. Style Kits include the page builder widget setup, options and color settings, along with any internal assets required such as fonts or icons.</p>\n<h4><strong>Child Theme</strong></h4>\n<p>Used when a style kit is not enough and usually includes multiple stylesheets, additional scripts and a functions file defining custom Actions allow you to inject a custom function or bit of code into a specific place.</p>\n<p>You can create a custom Action using the main WordPress <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/add_action" target="_blank">Action API</a> to add or remove code from an existing core action by specifying any <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Action_Reference" target="_blank">existing Hook</a>. Thus the term &#8220;hooking.&#8221; Layers also offers an Action API for hooking into our own custom actions.</p>\n<p><strong>For example:</strong> You may want to <strong>add</strong> code to the footer of Layers. This can be accomplished by writing new function containing your custom code, then Hooking it to the <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Action_Reference/wp_footer" target="_blank">wp_footer</a> core action OR use the Layers Action API to take advantage of better placement.</p>\n<p>The action will output a custom element just above the copyright bar, for instance. Custom Actions differ from custom <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Glossary#Filter" target="_blank">Filters</a> because custom Actions allow you to <strong>add or remove</strong> code from existing Actions. Whereas custom Filters allow you to <strong>replace</strong> specific data (such as a variable or CSS class) found within an existing Action.</p>\n<h5><strong>From the WordPress Codex:</strong></h5>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API#Actions" target="_blank">Actions</a></li>\n<li><a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Action_Reference" target="_blank">Action Reference</a></li>\n<li><a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/add_action" target="_blank">add_action()</a> actions and filters</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Learn more about <a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/child-theme-author-guide/" target="_blank">making Child Themes for Layers</a></p>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>WordPress sites are incredibly flexible things, so it is no wonder it powers 25% of the internet. With a little time and planning, you can turn your Layers site into literally anything by applying one or a combination of these techniques. Keep an eye on this space as we cover specific CSS tricks and take a closer look at some of the awesome free and premium extensions and child themes to help you achieve your goals.</p>\n<p>What are some of your favorite tools for WordPress customization? Share with us below!</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/the-essential-guide-to-wordpress-theme-customization-for-beginners/">The Essential Guide to WordPress Theme Customization for Beginners</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com">Layers</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:104:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/the-essential-guide-to-wordpress-theme-customization-for-beginners/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:48:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:39:"10 Ways to Use the Layers Slider Widget";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:65:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/10-ways-use-layers-slider-widget/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:74:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/10-ways-use-layers-slider-widget/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 05 Nov 2015 16:41:45 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"Tips";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"layers slider";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"slider widget";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://www.layerswp.com/?p=1902";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:488:"<p>In this featurette, we have compiled a number of our most popular tutorials to show you how to take your Layers pages further with the Slider Widget. You''ll learn how to incorporate it into a Hero-style page layout, vanity cards, slideshows and more.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/10-ways-use-layers-slider-widget/">10 Ways to Use the Layers Slider Widget</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com">Layers</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Vail Joy";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15393:"<p>In <a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/layers-hotfix-1-2-7/" target="_blank">Layers 1.2.6</a>, we introduced a revamped  slider using the newest <a href="http://www.idangero.us/swiper/" target="_blank">swiper.js</a> and <a href="https://philipwalton.github.io/solved-by-flexbox/" target="_blank">Flexbox</a> to improve responsiveness and content layout flexibility. Slider options were also extended to include three animation types and better support for auto-sizing. Be sure to update Layers to take advantage of these and many other enhancements.</p>\n<p>You can hardly find a landing page on any modern WordPress website that is not utilizing a slider in some form or another. They are usually a breeze to set up, inherently customizable, and allow you to showcase creative content in a relatively simple way. Designers love using them to tell a compelling story, and WordPress users love them for promoting several aspects of their business in one interactive space. When implemented well, sliders grab website visitor attention and offer a familiar browsing experience.</p>\n<p>But plopping a slider onto your home page without a visual plan and contextual purpose will fail to manifest all these good things. Simply having an element on your page that slides things but does not connect with your visitors has the unfortunate result of entering their visual &#8220;blind spot,&#8221; where the slider is ignored and scrolled past.  While bold colors, stunning photography or trend-forward textures are a good start for grabbing the eye, what your slider communicates and how it does it will determine most whether someone will take the time to interact with it longer than a few seconds.</p>\n<p>The Layers Slider Widget is a key building block for your Layers pages &#8211; not just because of its customization options, but because of its incredible versatility. This widget was designed to transform into a wide variety of uses, from single-column static content to photo slideshows. It is not limited to the top-most position on your page, and can be used multiple times. Let&#8217;s take a look at some of the many ways you can configure this widget to bring out its best potential.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1910 size-full" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/traditional.jpg" alt="traditional" width="584" height="256" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/traditional-300x132.jpg 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/traditional.jpg 584w" sizes="(max-width: 584px) 100vw, 584px" /></p>\n<h3>Traditional Content Slider</h3>\n<p>When you first add a Layers Slider Widget to your builder pages, this is what you&#8217;ll get &#8211; a simple, 3-Slide element for highlighting new content on your site. You probably encounter content sliders on a daily basis when browsing news or magazine websites. For sites that are updated often, the Slider Widget is also a popular way to direct visitor traffic to specific features or editorials. For example, you might pair a Slider Widget with a Posts Widget, with the Slider focusing on the latest opinion posts, and the Post Widget displaying the most recent content from all categories. Content sliders are also a common element of e-Commerce websites, where they are used to promote specific products, or categories.</p>\n<p><a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/layers-slider-widget/" target="_blank">Learn the Basics of the Layers Slider Widget</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><img class="alignnone wp-image-1911 size-full" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/pagetitle.jpg" alt="pagetitle" width="584" height="256" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/pagetitle-300x132.jpg 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/pagetitle.jpg 584w" sizes="(max-width: 584px) 100vw, 584px" /></h3>\n<h3>Simple Page Title</h3>\n<p>Most people don&#8217;t think of a slider in terms of what a single slide element can be used for. At its most basic, the Slider is simply a single column of content, with several layout options, which can be duplicated and stacked and animated. Single slides are synonymous with content blocks and can serve a similar purpose to the Content Widget with one grand advantage &#8211; you can control the height of the slider.</p>\n<p>Page titles are found atop most interior pages, but may also be used to create a static header on your Home and landing pages.</p>\n<p>The single title configuration can be used to mimic the Title Banner at the top of other Layers pages such as the Shop, Blog or Blank template, and customized easily for height, background and alignment.</p>\n<p>Learn Now: <a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/how-to-create-hero-headers-with-the-layers-slider-widget/" target="_blank">How To Create Hero Headers With The Layers Slider Widget</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone" src="http://docs.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/Image-2015-11-04-at-4.00.09-PM.png" alt="" width="600" height="298" /></p>\n<h3>Hero Header</h3>\n<p>Like a bat-signal, the hero-style header layout is formed around a single content section that takes up the first fold of a page to communicate one clear goal. This can be a first impression for your brand or business, and is seen most on design, portfolio and content-driven sites such as Medium, as well as our own websites here at Layers. This tutorial takes the Simple Page Title and blows it up, then adds a dash of Custom CSS to make it sparkle (not literally.)</p>\n<p>Learn Now: <a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/how-to-create-hero-headers-with-the-layers-slider-widget/" target="_blank">How To Create Hero Headers With The Layers Slider Widget</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Vanity Cards &amp; Site Intros</h3>\n<p>Remember the days when Flash rules the web and everyone had a cool animated intro? If you&#8217;re a designer, you&#8217;re probably groaning inwardly at the memory, but when done right, intros add a touch of movement and personality to websites that want to connect with the viewer. Vanity Cards are commonly created with video, which is best if you want full-motion effects and several frames. However, the Slider Widget can be setup to engage your visitors through a handful of slides and its Fade animation &#8211; a trick of modern web design that helped Flash lose its foothold.</p>\n<p>Learn Now: <a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/how-to-create-a-fading-intro-with-the-layers-slider-widget/" target="_blank">How To Create A Fading Intro With The Layers Slider Widget</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><a href="http://sites.layerswp.com/weather/" target="_blank"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1912 size-full" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/producttour.jpg" alt="producttour" width="584" height="256" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/producttour-300x132.jpg 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/producttour.jpg 584w" sizes="(max-width: 584px) 100vw, 584px" /></a></h3>\n<h3>Product Tours</h3>\n<p>Sliders just seem to be made for marketing products, but it is important product sliders stay focused on the visuals, tagline and core message, as you would expect from a print ad in a magazine. Large quantities of information can overwhelm visitors if presented all at once, so getting straight to the point reduces distraction and increases the chance they will stick around.</p>\n<p>Sliding sliders are most effective when you have a set of information, like paragraphs on a page, that you want to be presented in sequence. If each slide is trying to showcase a totally different thing with a different call to action, your visitors are not likely to sit and watch it long enough to interact with every message.</p>\n<p>A product slider should begin with introducing the product, then move on to highlighting its features or promoting ways to extend it. Setting up the widget to promote your product or app is as simple as adding it to your page, then customizing the starting configuration and content. The following tutorial will introduce you to the Advanced option of the widget for applying techniques such as replacing the button with an App Store image.</p>\n<p>Learn Now: <a class="question-title" href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/how-to-use-the-advanced-design-bar-option-to-add-custom-classes-to-widgets/" rel="bookmark">How to Use the Advanced Design Bar Option for Custom Classes, Margins and Padding</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><img class="alignnone" src="http://docs.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/jumbo.jpg" alt="" width="600" height="300" /></h3>\n<h3>Jumbo Photo</h3>\n<p>The Layers Slider Widget has three primary sizes, presented as Layouts. These are Boxed, Full Width and Full Screen. Like Hero headers, the Full Screen layout  is a gorgeous way to showcase visually-driven content on sites such as travel blogs, photo album pages or creative portfolios. This configuration combines auto-scaling background images with a simple custom style to place the Title and Excerpt at the bottom of the slide, so your images take center-stage.</p>\n<p>Learn Now:<a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/how-to-create-a-jumbo-photo-slider-with-the-layers-slider-widget/" target="_blank"> How To Create A Jumbo Photo Slider With The Layers Slider Widget</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><img class="alignnone" src="http://docs.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/slideshow.jpg" alt="" width="630" height="376" /></h3>\n<h3>Photo Slideshow</h3>\n<p>The Layers Slider has two primary ways of handling images: the background image and the featured image. You can use either to create a slideshow with the Slider widget, but using background images has a few disadvantages – you can’t link them, they are not inherently “responsive” (i.e. they do not automagically scale with the slide on mobiles) and they cannot affect the slider’s overall size. Featured images, on the other hand, can do all these things, but cannot be overlayed with text by default. This tutorial provides steps for creating a slideshow using featured images to give you the most control over linking and presentation.</p>\n<p>Learn Now:<a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/how-to-create-a-photo-slideshow-with-the-layers-slider-widget/" target="_blank"> How To Create A Photo Slideshow With The Layers Slider Widget</a></p>\n<h3></h3>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone" src="http://docs.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/Image-2015-11-04-at-3.21.19-PM.png" alt="" width="602" height="138" /></p>\n<h3>Testimonials</h3>\n<p>You don&#8217;t need a special plugin to add quotes or testimonials to your page. The Layers Slider offers an auto-sizing option and rich text editing to make creating testimonial slides in several styles easy and fun.</p>\n<p>Learn Now: <a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/how-to-create-testimonials-with-the-layers-slider-widget/" target="_blank">How To Create Testimonials With The Layers Slider Widget</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img class="alignnone wp-image-1913" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/video.jpg" alt="video" width="600" height="177" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/video-300x88.jpg 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/video.jpg 574w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></p>\n<h3>Music &amp; Videos</h3>\n<p>Layers allows you to use any multi-media URL supported by <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Embeds" target="_blank">oEmbed</a> in place of the Featured Image in Widgets and Posts. This opens up a variety of ways to showcase videos, playlists and even Tweets in any Slider configuration. If you want to feature a single video and really make it pop, the following configuration used on our example page uses a centered &#8220;featured image&#8221;, does away with extra text, and makes use of the little-understood padding controls under the Advanced Option:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Set your Slider <strong>Layout</strong> to Full Width</li>\n<li>Under the Design Bar&#8217;s <strong>Slider</strong> option, check Auto-Height, then uncheck Show Slider Dots and Auto-Play Slides</li>\n<li>In your first slide (or only slide &#8211; it&#8217;s up to you!), click the Background Image button in the slide&#8217;s toolbar and add a nice background image. For best results, choose an image that jives with your video&#8217;s style and color scheme. For non-tiling images, be sure to use large images at least 2000px wide with the <strong>Stretch</strong> option enabled.</li>\n<li>Click the <strong>Featured Image</strong> option and add your media&#8217;s oEmbed URL to the Video URL field.</li>\n<li>Remove the <strong>Title, Excerpt</strong> and <strong>Button</strong> content.</li>\n<li>Click the <strong>Advanced</strong> button on the Design Bar, and enter <strong>0</strong> into the <strong>Padding</strong> option&#8217;s Top and Bottom.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Learn more about <a class="question-title" href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/how-to-embed-audio-video-with-layers/" rel="bookmark">How to Embed Audio &amp; Video with Layers</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><a href="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cta-slider.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1914" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cta-slider.jpg" alt="cta-slider" width="600" height="177" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cta-slider-300x88.jpg 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cta-slider.jpg 574w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a></h3>\n<h3>Call To Action Banner</h3>\n<p>Call-to-action banners are useful for promoting specific pages on your site such as a Sale or Features page, or a specific post or product. The Layers Slider Widget allows you to easily create a variety of promo section styles that combine text, images and buttons. This tutorial walks you through how to configure both the Content and the Slider Widget for a Tagline &amp; Button style banner that can be placed at the bottom of a Layers builder page, or in a 1 column Site Footer to show across all pages on the site.</p>\n<p>Learn Now: <a class="question-title" href="http://docs.layerswp.com/doc/how-to-create-a-call-to-action-banner/" rel="bookmark">How to Create a Call to Action Banner With Layers Widgets</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><a href="http://docs.layerswp.com/slider-widget-examples/" target="_blank"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1909" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/examples1.jpg" alt="examples" width="599" height="307" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/examples1-300x154.jpg 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/examples1.jpg 660w" sizes="(max-width: 599px) 100vw, 599px" /></a></p>\n<p>We probably haven&#8217;t even thought of all the ways to use the stock slider, with or without Custom CSS. What are some ways you are using the widget on your sites? Tell us in the comments!</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/10-ways-use-layers-slider-widget/">10 Ways to Use the Layers Slider Widget</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com">Layers</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/10-ways-use-layers-slider-widget/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"1";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:48:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:48:"What Research Tells Us Your School Website Needs";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:71:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/research-tells-us-school-website-needs/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:79:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/research-tells-us-school-website-needs/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 21 Oct 2015 13:19:44 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"Tips";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"school website";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:18:"university website";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://www.layerswp.com/?p=1771";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:561:"<p>More and more potential students and their parents go online to research schools before ever committing to an on-site tour. Not only is the school or university website a critical resource for all things class-related, it is a storefront for the business of education. What makes your school the best choice?</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/research-tells-us-school-website-needs/">What Research Tells Us Your School Website Needs</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com">Layers</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Vail Joy";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15942:"<p>Just about every University has a website, and public schools are quickly catching up, but being online is about as effective as putting up a lemonade stand on a freeway these days, especially if the site is left to decay in the throes of outdated code and functionality.</p>\n<p>WordPress is an exceptional choice for powering educational sites thanks to its familiar publishing interface, ease of administration, open-source code, and outstanding variety of professionally-designed plugins. Universities such as <a href="http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/" target="_blank">Harvard</a>, <a href="http://music.cornell.edu/" target="_blank">Cornell</a>,<a href="http://museum.mit.edu/150/" target="_blank"> MIT</a> and <a href="http://ourenvironment.berkeley.edu/" target="_blank">Berkeley</a>, among many more, all use WordPress! The platform alone doesn&#8217;t make for a good website, though, and is only your starting point to building engaging content.</p>\n<p>All schools are unique to a degree, of course, but most of their websites offer similar content. Schools an Universities in a close geographical region or with similar concentrations also share similar target audiences. In a bid to grab the attention of this audience, these websites often do one of two things wrong &#8211; they make a site that is too academic, packed with information bridging several sub-sites for each department, or they make it too commercial, glossing over meaningful content in favor of high quality visuals and marketing.</p>\n<div id="attachment_1884" style="width: 551px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/university_website.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-1884" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/university_website.png" alt="Image Credit: xkcd" width="541" height="378" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/university_website-300x210.png 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/university_website.png 541w" sizes="(max-width: 541px) 100vw, 541px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Image Credit: <a href="https://xkcd.com/773/" target="_blank">xkcd</a></p></div>\n<p>The key is marrying these two concepts to produce a visually pleasing and easy to navigate site that puts the information students and parents need at the forefront.</p>\n<h3>Interesting vs Informative</h3>\n<p><a href="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1897" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-2-1024x185.jpg" alt="classroom-2" width="1024" height="185" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-2-300x54.jpg 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-2-1024x185.jpg 1024w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-2.jpg 1241w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>\n<p dir="ltr">The single most important thing to nail down is your audience priorities.  There are established trends and statistics that illuminate some universal best practices we can follow when planning or revamping an educational website, but it doesn&#8217;t hurt to offer a survey to existing students asking them what they looked for prior to applying, and after beginning attendance. For example, if your school offers both on-campus and online courses, make clarifying the admission process a priority. If your school offers several athletic scholarships, dedicate a page to your athletic program. If, however, you are known for your arts programs, then you will want to spend more time crafting content around topics that are the main focus of your school.</p>\n<p dir="ltr">The most universal topic at any university, college or charter school, is cost.  What are the tuition rates and payment options? What about student housing, material costs and online discounts? Potential students rank this is as one of their <a href="http://www.nngroup.com/articles/college-students-on-the-web/" target="_blank">top priorities </a>when researching schools online. This audience is also often too wary or impatient to want to deal with the hard-sell &#8211; you know, that tactic where you don&#8217;t publicize costs in order to force contact with an admissions agent. This wastes time for both individuals.</p>\n<h3 dir="ltr">Student Priorities</h3>\n<p dir="ltr">Data provided by an <a href="http://www.nngroup.com/reports/college-students-on-the-web/" target="_blank">extensive report </a>from Nielsen Norman Group on student and parent website usage and design standards defines a set of priorities that are not all too surprising. They studied both prospective students and parents to determine which priorities rank highest for both audiences and which were of least concern.</p>\n<ol>\n<li dir="ltr">Cost</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Academic Programs</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Scholarships</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Financial Aid</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Course Details</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Housing</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Enrollment/Admissions</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Campus/Student Life</li>\n</ol>\n<p><a href="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Priorities-When-Browsing-School-Websites1.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1895" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Priorities-When-Browsing-School-Websites1.png" alt="Priorities When Browsing School Websites" width="800" height="450" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Priorities-When-Browsing-School-Websites1-300x169.png 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Priorities-When-Browsing-School-Websites1.png 800w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<h3 dir="ltr">Parent Interests</h3>\n<p dir="ltr">Grade schools are the newest member of the educational website family, and as such are struggling the most with how to balance presentation with information. According to the NNG&#8217;s report on student and parent use of educational websites, grade-school age groups and their parents require a very different kind of approach in the overall design. Parents, who are usually not the web-savviest, need simplicity. Both parents and their children additionally benefit from an age-appropriate design that is fun, uses minimal amounts of text, and places day-to-day tasks as a top priority.</p>\n<p dir="ltr">These tasks might include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li dir="ltr">Bus Schedules</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Event, Holiday and Conference Schedules</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Cafeteria Menus and Costs</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Supply and Book Costs</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Athletic and After-School Programs, With Online Registration</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Curriculum or downloadable materials</li>\n<li dir="ltr">Faculty and Emergency Contacts</li>\n</ul>\n<h3><img class="alignnone wp-image-1898" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-routes-1024x617.jpg" alt="classroom-routes" width="715" height="431" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-routes-300x181.jpg 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-routes-1024x617.jpg 1024w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-routes.jpg 1268w" sizes="(max-width: 715px) 100vw, 715px" /></h3>\n<h3>Mythbusting</h3>\n<p>A school website shouldn&#8217;t cater to just parents or just students. In NNG&#8217;s research, they found three major myths that contribute to poor school website design planning:</p>\n<h4>Myth #1: Young People Are Tech Wizards</h4>\n<p>While it is true that the younger generation are more familiar with the web, it does not mean they are masters at searching or content comprehension. They depend on intuitive interfaces and direct language as much as their parents, and tend to be more impatient. This means the information they need should be within a few clicks or less, and each topic confined to a single space that does not span several more pages or sub-sites.</p>\n<p>In particular, students <strong>don&#8217;t like to learn new user interface styles</strong>. They prefer websites that employ well-known interaction patterns. If a site doesn&#8217;t work in the expected manner, most students lose patience and leave rather than try to decode a difficult design.</p>\n<h4>Myth #2: Students Want Multimedia and Fancy Design</h4>\n<p>Even an art school can suffer from overly-conceptual web design that sacrifices straight-forward navigation for abstraction or cutting-edge tricks. The school site itself needs to remain familiar, info-centric and cross-browser compatible.</p>\n<p>Students often judge sites on how they look. But they usually prefer sites that look <strong>clean and simple </strong>rather than flashy and busy. One user said that websites should <em>&#8220;stick to simplicity in design, but not be old-fashioned. Clear menus, not too many flashy or moving things because it can be quite confusing.&#8221; </em>Leave the fancy showcasing to the student portfolios.</p>\n<h4>Myth #3: You Need Your Social Sites To Market The School</h4>\n<p>A huge number of people use social media, and as such many businesses can benefit from connecting with potential customers, fans or readers through these networks. However, students associate Facebook and similar sites with private discussions, not with corporate marketing. NNG found that when students want to learn about a university, school or organization, they turn to search engines to find that organization&#8217;s official website. They don&#8217;t look for the organization&#8217;s Facebook page.</p>\n<p>This isn&#8217;t to say your school doesn&#8217;t need social media. Facebook and Twitter are fantastic ways to keep current students and parents aware of current and upcoming events, general campus chatter and the school football game score.</p>\n<h3>Designing an Effective School Website in WordPress</h3>\n<p><a href="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1896" src="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-1-1024x326.jpg" alt="classroom-1" width="1024" height="326" srcset="http://d2m1ao5c1vnep2.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-1-300x95.jpg 300w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-1-1024x326.jpg 1024w, http://www.layerswp.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/classroom-1.jpg 1241w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>\n<p>Now that you know what students and parents are gunning for, you need to figure out how to best deliver that content. We know that young people tend to gravitate towards visual content like videos, images and infographics, whereas parents are more interested in facts and numbers, so make sure those are easy to find. If important information like cost, graduation rate and academic information is buried too deeply in menus and tables,  or presented too shallowly like a TV commercial, you may lose potential students. Time and attention spans are limited, so invest in content that provides the most relevant information, in the simplest and clearest manner.</p>\n<p>We will touch more on configuration specifics in future articles, but for now, we have summarized some of the best tools for the task to get you started:</p>\n<h4>Layers + Classroom Child Theme</h4>\n<p>Chances are if you&#8217;re reading this blog, you have an idea of what Layers can do. If you are new to theme frameworks, Layers provides a clean, functionality-driven foundation for building WordPress sites that is based on progressive coding standards and using what the WordPress core provides to avoid additional bloat.</p>\n<p><a href="http://themeforest.net/item/classroom-responsive-wordpress-school-theme/13248588?ref=obox&amp;utm_source=layerswp&amp;utm_campaign=blogpost" target="_blank">The Classroom child theme</a> provides several professionally designed preset-page layouts and starter content you can customize, which focus on the key priorities we have covered here. It includes an Events widget for quickly showcasing anything from football games to workshops. Classroom provides a perfect start for grade schools, charters or independent learning programs, but can easily be converted into a full-featured university site thanks to the power of Layers customization.</p>\n<p>Learn more about Classroom in our <a href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/10/learn-a-thing-or-two-with-our-new-school-theme-classroom/" target="_blank">Launch Post</a>. For school projects looking for a wider variety of presets, we also recommend you <a href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/09/lets-play/" target="_blank">check out Play</a>.</p>\n<h4>Sensei LMS</h4>\n<p><a href="http://www.woothemes.com/products/sensei/" target="_blank">Sensei</a> is an amazing, low-cost LMS plugin from our friends at WooThemes. With the Sensei plugin you can create courses, write lessons, add quizzes, set lesson and course pre-requisites, and manage user registration. You can also charge for courses thanks to integration with the free WooCommerce plugin, making this an excellent way to offer online programs or one-off courses. Sensei can be extended to add functionality for things like self-pacing, certification or progress badges to power anything from a university-level curriculum to a continued education service such as CodeAcademy.</p>\n<h4>WooCommerce + StoreKit</h4>\n<p>We&#8217;ve already mentioned how the free WooCommerce plugin can help you offer online courses and online payments, but it can also be used as a point-of-sale management system for books and materials, commissary, tickets or any other tangible goods students need. The<a href="http://codecanyon.net/item/storekit-woocommerce-for-layers/11223808?ref=obox&amp;utm_source=layerswp&amp;utm_campaign=blogpost" target="_blank"> StoreKit extension </a>works with Layers to allow you to easily customize colors, sidebars and shop element visibility, and provides additional widgets for building custom landing pages for showcasing courses or products.</p>\n<h4>The Events Calendar</h4>\n<p>It is one thing to offer schedule information on your school or university website, and another to do it in a format that is clear and easy to scan. Grids are a good way to do this for small groups of information, or when you want to include visuals like maps or button links for registration. For ongoing schedules such as lunch or athletics, a calendar is often better. Use this<a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/the-events-calendar/" target="_blank"> free plugin</a> to manage events, course calendars or schedules, and display them in interactive calendar and list views on your site.</p>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>All of this information may make a school website project seem overhwelming, but it’s good to remember how parents and students can feel the same way about all of the information the web throws at them. Think about what you look for when visiting an educational site &#8211; your intuition is often right. As for design, you don&#8217;t need to conform to the boxy layouts of old &#8211; don’t be afraid to try new ways of presenting familiar patterns. Establish a rapport with your visitors through newsletters or surveys, record your findings, and continue to evolve your content strategy to aid your university’s digital success.</p>\n<p><em>What have you found lacking in school or university sites? If you have worked on an educational website project, which elements have you found to be the most successful?</em></p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/research-tells-us-school-website-needs/">What Research Tells Us Your School Website Needs</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.layerswp.com">Layers</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:76:"http://www.layerswp.com/2015/11/research-tells-us-school-website-needs/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:4:"href";s:29:"http://www.layerswp.com/feed/";s:3:"rel";s:4:"self";s:4:"type";s:19:"application/rss+xml";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:44:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/";a:2:{s:12:"updatePeriod";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"hourly";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:15:"updateFrequency";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"1";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:"type";i:128;s:7:"headers";a:11:{s:4:"date";s:29:"Mon, 28 Dec 2015 07:37:03 GMT";s:6:"server";s:22:"Apache/2.2.22 (Ubuntu)";s:12:"x-powered-by";s:22:"PHP/5.3.10-1ubuntu3